1/15/01
  Matt fixed some old code in statmux.  Also removed his last changes of
  pointer.  The resulting code runs fine without reset.  Asked him to 
  check in his changes.

  Overnight test result:
    My box ran fine without problem.  (with 0.3 sec black time)

    Wayne's box die due to a hanging timeout.  Seems like a splice is done,
    but spctrl still detect timeout afterward.  New problem.  Need more study.

  Testing get "## AF size 229" error

  BUG: while the monitor is in checkSpCtrl(), processing the splice request
       queue, the splice control task frees up the request that monitor
       task is on.  As a result, monitor task is now processing the free
       queue, which cause the reset.
  FIX: use interrupt protection for the entire checkSpCtrl().

  Kernel issues:
    According to Fang, the msgSend() function may cause task switch because
    the second dmaWordCopy() may be blocked and caused a task switch to
    even a lower priority task.  Since dmaWordCopy() is intelligent to
    actually use DMA if the DMA size is > 32 words, this will not always
    happen.  However, when DMA is used, we cannot disable interrupt, because
    otherwise the interrupt of DMA completion will not be received, causing
    a deadlock.

    Therefore, in general, do not call dbgPrint() when interrupt is disabled.

  Seems like the frequent reset problem has something to do with the input
  video stopped detection mechanism, especially when SeaChange Ad Server
  is used.

  Created new ytse-ts to study the time stamp accuracy issue.
  Two approaches: 
    - if mapped TS and regenerated TS are different by a small amount (<5),
      then use the regenerated value adjusted by 1 instead.
    - use a variable in chanInfo to track the remaining DI when inserting
      glue picture.

  According MPEG-2 frame rate table, the highest precision up to a field time
  is 1/8 of a 90 kHz clock!  This becomes 1/16 for 45 kHz clock.


